Heraclitus of Ephesus c. 535 – 475 BCE
Region / Tradition: Ionia (Greek)
School / Movement: Pre-Socratic (The Ephesian School)

Core Domains
Metaphysics: Flux (Panta Rhei); Unity of Opposites; Fire as the Arche.

Epistemology: The Logos (Universal Reason); Empiricism tempered by insight.

Ethics: Self-knowledge; Character as destiny.

Political: Rule by the "best" (aristocracy of intellect) over the "uncomprehending" masses.

Religion: Critique of traditional ritual; The divine as the cosmic process.

Central Questions
What problem(s) were they trying to solve: The nature of change and the underlying order that governs a world in constant motion.

What tension or paradox defines their work: The Unity of Opposites—how things can be both the same and different simultaneously (e.g., "The way up and the way down are one and the same").

What question do they inherit: The Milesian search for a single material principle (Arche).

What question do they bequeath: "If everything changes, is there any permanent truth?" and "How does the mind connect to the universal laws of the cosmos?"

Key Ideas
Concept 1: Panta Rhei (Everything Flows): The famous doctrine that one cannot step into the same river twice, as new waters are always flowing in.

Concept 2: The Logos: A universal objective law or "word" that coordinates all things, which most people fail to hear or understand.

Concept 3: Fire as the Arche: Fire is the fundamental element because it is a process rather than a "thing"—it is constantly consuming, transforming, and moving.

Concept 4: War/Strife as Father: The belief that conflict between opposites (hot/cold, day/night) is necessary for existence; without tension, the universe would collapse.

Method / Style
Aphoristic and Paradoxical.
Known as "The Obscure," he wrote in riddles to force the reader into a state of active thinking. He believed truth was hidden in plain sight but required a "soul that speaks the language" of the Logos.

Influences
The Milesians: He accepted their search for a single substance but rejected their "static" elements (water/air) for the "dynamic" element (fire).

Personal Solitude: His notorious misanthropy and withdrawal from society shaped his "elitist" intellectual stance.

Impact
Immediate reception: Seen as a difficult, gloomy, and arrogant figure.

Long-term influence: Formed the "Ever-Becoming" half of the great debate against Parmenides’ "Being." Heavily influenced Plato, the Stoics, Hegel, and Nietzsche.

Modern relevance: Precursor to Process Philosophy and the dialectical method; his "strife of opposites" mirrors modern concepts of entropy and equilibrium.

Critiques
Internal contradictions: If everything is constantly changing, his own statement that "everything changes" would theoretically have to change as well.

Famous objections: Cratylus (his follower) took it further, saying you can't even step into the same river once, leading to a total breakdown of language and meaning.

Archetypal Summary
Heraclitus as the dark prophet of the flame, teaching that stability is an illusion born of perfectly balanced tensions.

